I have gone with a significantly higher set of numbers than the consensus. It feels to me like there are a couple of big picture scenarios to consider. One, we have and keep this under control - effective social distancing and or contact tracing allows Government to essentially control the number of daily cases to keep the NHS from being overwhelmed. We then essentially have a choice about the trade off between the number of cases and the "economic" and other harm people are concerned about. We can either attempt to kill the virus as something spreading in the UK by keeping really strict measures in place - in that case, let's say we have 3k cases per day for the next 10 days, 2k cases per day for the following 10 and then sub 100 for the following 48 - that keeps us in the sub 180k bucket, but if it is even 3.5k for the next 10 days 2,750 for the following 15 and 200 for the remaining 43, that gets us above 180k. Let's say if we did choose to go down that route, we would have 75% chance of staying sub 180k and 25% chance of ending up in the 180-260k bucket. Then let's say we choose to focus more on opening things up. Let's say as above, cases gradually drop to 2k but then we allow them to stay there, that generally gets us in the 180 - 260k cases, but if misjudged a little and end up with 2.5k cases for the last 30 days on average, that gets us in the 260 - 340k bucket and even if we overrun quite a bit but still manage to get the lid back on if things go really wrong, we probably manage to keep within that bucket. However, if we "lose control" and get back on an exponential curve and get uncontrolled spreading, we could easily exceed the 420k cases (and that is probably more likely than the 340 - 420k cases range in that instance). So let's say if we go down that route, we are talking about a 40% chance of ending up in the 180 - 260k bucket (i.e. keeping it under control), 50% a slight misjudgement (260 - 340k) and 10% out of control (420k+). Between the try to crush it and try to have some controlled spread, I think we are probably 25/75. Putting those all together gives me 19% in sub 180k, 36% in 180-260k, 38% in 260-340k and 8% in 420k. Let's say there is also a 5% chance this is a false dawn and it is then going to be a real struggle, so we are 50/50 between 340 - 420k (i.e. things go up but we do get them back under control relatively quickly) and 420k plus (big struggle). HOWEVER, one thing I do not want to miss is that we could well start to see a real increase in testing as part of these containment measures. Let's say cases are currently unreported versus what they will be going forward and moves everything up by a bucket.. Let's say there is a 50% chance that happens. Gives me my final numbers.
